# Condukt Sandbox Demo

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:condukt, "~> 0.5"},
  {:terrarium, "~> 0.9"},
  {:terrarium_exe, "~> 0.4"},
  {:kino, "~> 0.14"}
])
```

## Setup

Enter your z.ai API key (free at [open.bigmodel.cn](https://open.bigmodel.cn)). The exe.dev token is generated automatically from your SSH key.

```elixir
zai_key_input = Kino.Input.password("Z.ai API Key")
```

```elixir
zai_key = Kino.Input.read(zai_key_input)

if zai_key in [nil, ""] do
  Kino.interrupt!(:error, "Please enter your Z.ai API key above")
end

# Generate exe.dev token from SSH key
ssh_key_path = Path.expand("~/.ssh/id_ed25519")
payload = Base.url_encode64("{}", padding: false)

{sig_pem, 0} =
  System.shell(~s(printf '{}' | ssh-keygen -Y sign -f #{ssh_key_path} -n v0@exe.dev))

sig_b64 =
  sig_pem
  |> String.split("\n")
  |> Enum.reject(&String.starts_with?(&1, "---"))
  |> Enum.join()
  |> String.replace("+", "-")
  |> String.replace("/", "_")
  |> String.trim_trailing("=")

exe_token = "exe0.#{payload}.#{sig_b64}"

Kino.Markdown.new("✅ **Ready.** exe.dev token generated from `#{ssh_key_path}`")
```

## Define an Agent

This agent has access to the `Bash` tool. Notice there's **no mention of sandboxes** in the agent definition — sandbox support is transparent.

```elixir
defmodule DemoAgent do
  use Condukt

  @impl true
  def tools, do: [Condukt.Tools.Bash]

  @impl true
  def system_prompt do
    """
    You are a helpful assistant with access to a bash shell.
    When asked to explore or run commands, use the Bash tool.
    Keep responses concise.
    """
  end

  @impl true
  def model, do: "zai:glm-4.5-flash"

  @impl true
  def thinking_level, do: :off
end
```

## Run Locally

First, let's run the agent **locally** — tools execute on this machine.

```elixir
{:ok, local_agent} = DemoAgent.start_link(api_key: zai_key)

frame = Kino.Frame.new() |> Kino.render()
text_frame = Kino.Frame.new()
Kino.Frame.append(frame, text_frame)

Condukt.stream(local_agent, "What operating system is this? Run `uname -a` to find out.")
|> Enum.reduce("", fn
  {:text, chunk}, text ->
    text = text <> chunk
    Kino.Frame.render(text_frame, Kino.Markdown.new(text))
    text

  {:tool_call, name, _id, args}, text ->
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("🔧 `#{name}(#{inspect(args)})`"))
    text

  {:tool_result, _id, result}, text ->
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("📋 `#{String.slice(to_string(result), 0..200)}`"))
    # New text frame for the next response chunk
    text_frame = Kino.Frame.new()
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, text_frame)
    ""

  _, text ->
    text
end)

GenServer.stop(local_agent)
Kino.nothing()
```

## Run in a Sandbox

Now the same agent, same prompt — but tools execute inside an **exe.dev VM**.
The only difference is the `:sandbox` option at `start_link`.

```elixir
frame = Kino.Frame.new() |> Kino.render()
Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("**Starting sandbox...**"))

{:ok, sandbox_agent} =
  DemoAgent.start_link(
    api_key: zai_key,
    sandbox: %{
      provider: Terrarium.Providers.Exe,
      provider_opts: [token: exe_token]
    }
  )

Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("✅ **Sandbox provisioned.** Running prompt..."))

text_frame = Kino.Frame.new()
Kino.Frame.append(frame, text_frame)

Condukt.stream(sandbox_agent, "What operating system is this? Run `uname -a` to find out.")
|> Enum.reduce("", fn
  {:text, chunk}, text ->
    text = text <> chunk
    Kino.Frame.render(text_frame, Kino.Markdown.new(text))
    text

  {:tool_call, name, _id, args}, text ->
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("🔧 `#{name}(#{inspect(args)})`"))
    text

  {:tool_result, _id, result}, text ->
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("📋 `#{String.slice(to_string(result), 0..200)}`"))
    text_frame = Kino.Frame.new()
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, text_frame)
    ""

  _, text ->
    text
end)

GenServer.stop(sandbox_agent)
Kino.nothing()
```

## Compare

Notice the difference:

* **Local:** `uname -a` returns your Mac's kernel (Darwin)
* **Sandbox:** `uname -a` returns the exe.dev VM's kernel (Linux)

The agent code is identical. The sandbox is invisible to the agent and the LLM — only tool execution is transparently remote.

## How it Works

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant Proxy as Local Process<br/>(thin proxy)
    participant Session as Condukt.Session<br/>(in sandbox)
    participant LLM as LLM Provider
    participant Tools as Bash Tool<br/>(in sandbox)

    User->>Proxy: run("What OS is this?")
    Proxy->>Session: :peer.call(run)
    Session->>LLM: prompt + tools
    LLM-->>Session: tool_call: Bash("uname -a")
    Session->>Tools: Bash.execute("uname -a")
    Tools-->>Session: "Linux 6.x ..."
    Session->>LLM: tool_result
    LLM-->>Session: "You're running Linux..."
    Session-->>Proxy: {:ok, response}
    Proxy-->>User: response
```
